    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "List comprehensions, when used on massive datasets, build the entire resulting list in memory all at once, which is what causes the `MemoryError`. Think of it like trying to fit an entire mountain of rocks into a small bucket—it just won't fit! In contrast, generators yield items one by one as they are requested, meaning they only hold one item in memory at any given time. This makes them incredibly memory-efficient, perfect for handling those huge CSVs with pandas.\n\nTo use a generator instead, you typically replace the square brackets `[]` with parentheses `()` when defining the expression. This tells Python to create an iterator instead of a full list. For your CSV processing, you'll want to iterate over the generator output directly rather than trying to collect it into a list.\n\nFor example, instead of `[process(row) for row in large_data]`, you'd use `(process(row) for row in large_data)`. This lazy evaluation is the key difference.\n\nThis approach is much better for large-scale data processing, especially when dealing with files that are too big to comfortably fit into your system's RAM. It's a crucial technique when working with",
      "source": "target",
